HEADWORD: Coo
<hw>Coo</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Cooed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Cooing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To make a low repeated
cry or sound, like the characteristic note of pigeons or
doves.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The stockdove only through the forest <qex>cooes</qex>,⟦br⟧
Mournfully hoarse.</q> <rj><qau>Thomson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To show affection; to act in a loving way. See under
<er>Bill</er>, <pos>v. i.</pos></def> ⟦ldquo⟧Billing or
<xex>cooing</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Byron.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

